'''Tanabata Shrine''' (たなばたじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Kinjo 4-chōme, {{ill|lt=Kita Ward (Nagoya)|Q1207964|WD=Q1207964|lt=Kita Ward|1=Kita-ku, Nagoya}}, {{ill|lt=Nagoya|Q11751|WD=Q11751|1=Nagoya}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|WD=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. It is identified with "Tanabata Shrine" of Yamada District, {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}.

=== History ===
Until the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period|WD=Q184963}}, it was called '''Tendō'''. It is said that in the Sengoku period, during a punitive burning by {{ill|lt=Oda Nobunaga|Q171411|WD=Q171411|1=Oda Nobunaga}}, the shrine buildings and transmitted documents were burned, so the founding year is unknown. The early-Edo ''{{ill|lt=Kanbun Muramura Oboegaki|Q137766629|WD=Q137766629|1=Kanbunmuramuraoboegaki}}'' records "Tabata village... Tendō... Bizen exemption." It is also said that when {{ill|lt=Nagoya Castle|Q648629|WD=Q648629|1=Nagoya Castle}} was built, the shrine was moved to its current site by land substitution. {{ill|lt=Tsuda Masao|Q22123474|WD=Q22123474|1=Tsuda Masanari}} mentioned a theory that in earlier times it was located in "Ofuke no kaku-nai" (possibly in present {{ill|lt=Meijō Park|Q6810044|WD=Q6810044|1=Meijō Park}}). Around the current shrine is the Tanabatachō archaeological site where {{ill|lt=Yayoi pottery|Q11487461|WD=Q11487461|1=Yayoi pottery}} has been excavated.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it came under the control of {{ill|lt=Nagoya Tōshō-gū|Q3335117|WD=Q3335117|1=Nagoya Tōshō-gū}}, and during the {{ill|lt=Kan'ei|Q1192913|WD=Q1192913|1=Kan'ei}} era new shrine buildings were constructed by the {{ill|lt=Owari Domain|Q1062072|WD=Q1062072|1=Owari Domain}}. On the annual festival day of the old lunar {{ill|lt=July 7|Q839741|WD=Q839741|lt=7th day of the 7th month|1=July 7 (Lunisolar)}}, the domain lord visited and ordinary townspeople were also permitted to worship inside the enclosure; many records survive, including depictions in the {{ill|lt=Owari Meisho Zue|Q11465290|WD=Q11465290|1=Owari meisho zue}}.

After it was identified in the Edo period with Yamada District's "Tanabata Shrine" in the Engishiki Jinmyōchō, this became the accepted theory. In the {{ill|lt=Owari Kokunai Jinmyōchō|Q11041830|WD=Q11041830|1=Owari Kokunai Jinmyōchō}} it appears as "Junior Third Rank Upper, Keta-hata Tenjin," suggesting the shikinaisha Tanabata Shrine was also called Keta-hata Tenjin. The main reason this shrine was identified as Tanabata Shrine is that it was located in Tabata Village of {{ill|lt=Kasugai District|Q11513576|WD=Q11513576|1=Kasugai district}}, with similar village and shrine names. The {{ill|lt=Chōshū Fushi|Q137847623|WD=Q137847623|1=Chōshūfushi}} identifies Tanabata Shrine with Sansha Myōjin in {{ill|lt=Obata (Nagoya)|Q52158082|WD=Q52158082|lt=Obata Village|1=Obata}}, but late-Edo gazetteers including {{ill|lt=Owari-shi|Q137855962|WD=Q137855962|1=Owarishi}} consistently identify this shrine as Tanabata Shrine.

In the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|WD=Q3125096}}, when the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was implemented, it became a village shrine under the name Hachiman Shrine; in {{ill|lt=Taishō|Q329174|WD=Q329174|1=Taishō era}} 11 ({{ill|lt=1922|Q2165|WD=Q2165|1=1922}}) it became a designated village shrine. During {{ill|lt=World War II|Q362|WD=Q362|1=World War II}}, an {{ill|lt=anti-aircraft gun|Q21156889|WD=Q21156889|1=anti-aircraft gun}} battery was placed on shrine grounds, and much of the shrine forest known as "Tanabata Forest" was cut down. In the {{ill|lt=Nagoya Air Raid|Q2813858|WD=Q2813858|1=Bombing of Nagoya}} of May 14, {{ill|lt=1945|Q5240|WD=Q5240|1=1945}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 20), the same raid that destroyed Nagoya Castle's main keep, the shrine buildings were burned down. The current buildings were rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1964|Q2652|WD=Q2652|1=1964}} (Shōwa 39).

